description: Led six-member team and managed $1.8M ground satellite communications equipment. Oversaw revitalization and upgrade of equipment capable of providing classified and unclassified internet, high frequency radio, and telephonic capabilities. Team produced an unprecedented one year, 100 percent full capability rate from July 2012 to July 2013. Managed $7.3M in deployable command, control and communications equipment (Mobile Tactical Operations Center). Enabling 12-hr austere air base opening missions in support of humanitarian assistance and disaster response in the Pacific Ocean. Tactical Operations Center provides shelter, communications (both classified and unclassified), emergency operations, mission monitoring, and team development in support of humanitarian assistance and disaster response. Mobile Tactical Operations Center was successfully tested five times to full capacity, twice with international partners (Australia and Japan). Developed and implemented large spectrum austere airfield communications plan. Created long-term follow-on procedures to tackle multi-lateral international agency communications to support humanitarian aid, medical support, and security in permissive and non-permissive environments.

title: NCOIC, Mobile Command and Control
description: Developed impromptu command and control centers in Indonesia for 11 member team and created communication reach-back capability in support of US Presidential movement through East Asia. Fully operational command center was located within a secure hotel room equipped with encrypted internet, satellite telephone, land-line telephone, cellular telephone and peripherals to ensure success of no-fail POTUS mission Oversaw the direction of operational and situational reporting program. Program success was key to multiple East Asia POTUS travel missions and international exercises hosted by Guam. Operational reporting apprised top leadership of events at forward operating locations ensuring they had full information to make tough decisions. developed and maintained emergency operations checklists established, procured, and maintained command and control equipment requirements in support of humanitarian assistance and disaster response contingencies located on islands in the Pacific Ocean. Established, oversaw, maintained, and operated emergency operations and response center that supported 52 heavy aircraft lift missions, the coordination and transfer of 67,000 pounds of cargo and movement of 163 personnel. Provided positive command and control operations in support of the first multilateral humanitarian assistance and disaster relief exercise between the United States, Japan, Australia, and South Korea. Managed mobile operations center communication and communication training requirements. Initiated equipment audit and control over 350 line items and created positive control over $419,000 of equipment. Directed emergency action controller training and certified EA team within one month. Created encrypted radio issue and repair program ensuring emergency response team’s communications during disaster response and humanitarian aid operations.

title: NCOIC PRCC
description: Led three personnel in the coordination and monitoring of force status of four rescue agencies. Monitored recovery operations executed by rescue forces. Responsible for the alert and launch of Navy and Marine rescue helicopters and US Army ground support and security teams. Developed and implemented standard operating procedures and established operations rhythm. Established liaison, developed procedures, and coordinated with medical treatment facilities for receiving recovered personnel. Created situational reporting standards providing force movement and recovery status’ for incident commanders. ~Orchestrated the evacuation of a US Army soldier casualty from Ethiopia. The soldier was safely recovered and transported to friendly facilities for medical treatment. ~Coordinated with US, African and French agencies in the rescue of a 69 year old US American citizen from an overturned civilian sailboat 250 miles East off the coast of Madagascar. The American citizen was the sole survivor of the wreck and was safely transported to medical facilities. ~Synchronized US Special Forces and rescue agencies in the recovery of the Maersk Alabama cargo ship after the April 2009 Somali pirate attack 280 miles southeast of Eyl, Somalia. The captain and crew of the Maersk Alabama were successfully recovered.
